Data.  Discovery.  Better Health.
We’ve got the data. Only ICES holds all of Ontario’s 18 billion health related records – comprised of nearly a trillion data points!
We’ve made improvements to health. As a world-leading research institute, our trusted evidence changes policy and practice…and patient lives.
We need you for the discovery part.
Your skills, knowledge and curiosity can change the future of health care.
Come discover your value.

Introduction:

ICES is currently seeking a Health Information Analyst (HIA) to join ICES’ Data Quality and Information Management team. Reporting to the Manager, Data Quality, the Health Information Analyst will support the unique programming and analysis requirements of the research projects in a particular area such as Electronic Medical Records (EMR).

Responsibilities of the position include, but may not be limited to:

Responsible for data quality, analyzing, compiling, and validating Electronic Medical Records and Electronic Health Records at ICES;
Work with Investigators and other colleagues to define and create cohorts of patients based on individual project needs using a variety of techniques, including text mining;
Collaborate with Investigators and other colleagues to develop methods for analyzing Primary Care Electronic Medical Record data
Carry out analyses of results, and assist in the preparation of reports and manuscripts as the projects requires;
Use EMR data to develop algorithms that identify patients with chronic diseases;
Maintain documentation on all processes and manuals on the use of developed programs;
Act as a resource to staff and faculty who require knowledge about the strengths and limitations of the pertinent database;
Contribute to the creation of stored procedures and practice standards for Health Information Analysts at ICES;
Create research-ready, user-friendly, standardized SAS datasets for the ICES Data Repository;
Create and maintain SAS macros and other tools to facilitate and standardize data use.

Knowledge, skills and abilities required:
Master’s degree in Health Informatics or quantitative discipline such as biostatistics, epidemiology, health services research, or related field;
Excellent programming skills in SQL scripts and SQL Server, with strong understanding of relational databases;
