Introduction:
The ICES Research and Analysis Department is seeking a Senior Research Analyst to work collaboratively with ICES researchers, applying research methodology and knowledge of epidemiology in the context of health services administrative data. The successful applicant will report to the Research Program Manager. He/she will work collaboratively with the project team and Principal Investigator (PI); and will analytically lead projects with PIs, contribute significantly to the development of dataset creation and analytic plans, and work independently to complete analyses for assigned work with minimal supervision. He/she will demonstrate a comprehensive understanding of ICES data holdings and concepts of health services research. The Senior Research Analyst will have strong proficiency in advanced SAS programming skills including SQL and macro writing. This position will be of interest to candidates looking for a position that is methodologically challenging and enjoys working in a fast-paced environment where deliverables are expected within tight timelines.

Responsibilities of the position include, but may not be limited to:

Under supervision of a Research Program Manager and in collaboration with an ICES Methodologist, the Senior Research Analyst will perform the following duties:
Work with the PI, and/or other Epidemiologist/Project Manager/Associate Research Methodologist or Methodologist in developing data set creation plans, analysis plans, and ensuring check points are being done as part of process;
Develop SAS programs to extract and merge data from existing ICES databases according to data set creation plans and following analytic standards and guidelines;
Carry out statistical analysis on developed study cohorts according to specifications of project analysis plans;
Prepare and review analytic output (e.g., tables and reports);
Interpret results and contribute to manuscripts and/or other deliverables;
Assume role of ‘in-house expert’ for particular datasets (statistical methodology) and work towards developing and documenting a body of knowledge around datasets and resolving data issues as they arise;
Contribute to or lead the work in developing macros and templates;
Share content expertise with junior faculty and students as required;
May be asked to mentor junior analysts, contribute to ongoing continuing education within department based on expertise;
Work effectively and efficiently according to ICES policies, procedures, standards, workflow processes, documents and requirements (e.g., complete program and project; documentation according to ICES standards and guidelines);
May help prepare study cohorts for students or faculty;
May contribute to the writing of reports (technical reports/working papers/ICES publications/web-based summaries), abstracts, poster presentations, peer-reviewed publications and other relevant deliverables, in collaboration with the PI;
Strong interface with internal and external stakeholders in support of the project such as expert panels, committees and team meetings;
May facilitate the uptake of knowledge by local decision-makers across Ontario through the presentation of findings, education sessions, and one-on-one interactions as required;
May assume lead on other committees or activities within the department or ICES in support of ICES business plan as required;
May assist Research Program Manager with hiring for vacant positions; such as recruitment activities, candidate screening and interviewing as requested;
Perform other duties as assigned within the scope of the position.

Knowledge, Skills and Abilities Required:
in Biostatistics, Statistics, Epidemiology, or related field;
Extensive experience with health administrative databases;
A minimum 5 years of related experience;
Experience in or willingness to learn complex statistical analyses including predictive modeling, and multistate modeling;
At least five years of experience with SAS programming (including SQL, writing SAS macros) and other data management tools;
Strong understanding of the concepts of health services research and bio-statistical analytic techniques as applied to health services research;
An aptitude for research methodology;
Demonstrated attention to detail;
Able to work flexibly with changing priorities and under tight timelines;
Creativity in developing data measures and initiative in resolving data anomalies;
Facility with sophisticated programming algorithms;
Strong stakeholder management skills and experience in managing expectations and timelines;
Strong oral, written and interpersonal communication skills are essential.
 This role is a full-time permanent position located at ICES Central in Toronto.
